						resolutions from Turkie.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="Turkie" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>[p. 145: It is true that Thomas Aquinas is sharp, and that Duns Scotus is subtle. No one of the scholastics more than the witty William of Ockham. I praise them. 
				Give me the aphorism of Diogenes Laertius and Plutarch, Martial's epigrams, and Heywood's, Domenichi's and Guazzo's witticisms. With the 'Mensa Philosophica': Eliot's 'Dialogues',
				the instructive revealing of places and things: with Ascham's descriptions of the persons in German matters: for all discourses. These are the eloquent things of courtiers and this exactness
				of the world. Especially with Aristotle's economic and political artifices: with Mithridates' letter, and his speech against the Romans: with Marcantonio Gandino's 'Stratagemata'.] 
				Here also the secrets of the courts in the royal rhapsodies: the political aphorisms of Lipsius, Francesco Sansavino, and Lambert Daneau. Also of Machiavelli, Jean Bodin, and Francois Hotman.
				The Queen Mothers Golden Legend. Maurice Poncet resolutions from Turkie.</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
